The paper discusses the development of a comprehensive approach for quality modelling and assessment in software engineering, which involves a combination of constructive research and empirical studies. The paper focuses on the operationalisation of quality models, which is a key aspect of software engineering. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.SE (Software Engineering). The paper also discusses the use of technology-independent base quality models, which suggests a focus on programming languages and software development practices, making cs.PL (Programming Languages) and cs.SD (Software Development) likely sub-categories as well. The paper also discusses the use of empirical studies, which suggests a focus on data analysis and machine learning, making cs.CY (Computational Geometry) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the use of open-source tool support, which suggests a focus on software engineering tools and applications, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) a possible sub-category as well.
